    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>2 Bryanston S<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>.</placeName>
                    <date>Friday.</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir.</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Very many thanks for your most kind note. I write a line merely to say that I will not accept your invitation to breakfast as I always breakfast before 8 o’clock!<ref target="#foot.f2"/> If I should fail to be able to come, I now <hi rend="underline">know</hi> that I may call on you when I next come to London, but I heartily hope that I may be able to come—</p>
<p>Yours sincerely. | C. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The date is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10302.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from A. W. Bennett, 17 December 1875</ref>; in 1875 17 December 1875 was a Friday.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Bennett had invited CD to breakfast on Sunday 19 December 1875 (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10302.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from A. W. Bennett, 17 December 1875</ref>). CD evidently did visit, since Bennett mentioned showing his <hi rend="italic">Drosera</hi> preparations to him in Bennett 1876.</note>
        </div>        
            
